Japanese, Australian Stock Futures Decline on U.S. Outlook, Oil

-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 
2011-05-19T23:07:55Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-19/japanese-australian-stock-futures-decline-on-u-s-outlook-oil-price-drop.html
Japanese and Australian  stock futures 
fell as commodities declined and reports showed U.S. home sales
unexpectedly declined and manufacturing growth slowed, hampering
the recovery in the world’s biggest economy.  American depositary receipts of  Toyota Motor Corp. (7203) , the
world’s largest carmaker which gets 28 percent of its sales in
 North America , slid 0.1 percent from the closing share price in
Tokyo. Those of  Mitsubishi Corp. (8058) , Japan’s largest commodities
trader, declined 0.1 percent and  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) , Australia’s
No. 1 oil producer and the world’s biggest mining company, lost
1.8 percent after oil and metal prices dropped.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
June closed at 9,625 in Chicago yesterday, compared with 9,630
in Osaka,  Japan . They were bid in the pre-market at 9,630 in
Osaka, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on Australia’s S&P/ASX
200 Index slid 0.2 percent today. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index
rose 0.2 percent in Wellington.  “Expectations for the U.S. economic outlook are slightly
decreasing and there’s a mood investors are wary of buying
stocks,” said Norikazu Kitta, a strategist at Tokyo-based Nikko
Cordial Securities Inc. “However, the stable yen and gains in
the U.S. stocks are positive for the market.”  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index fell 0.1 percent
today. In New York, the index advanced 0.2 percent to 1,343.60
yesterday after a government report showing a bigger-than-
forecast drop in jobless claims bolstered optimism about the
economic recovery.  Home Sales Fall  Another report showed sales of existing homes unexpectedly
declined in April, indicating the industry is struggling to gain
traction as the economy expands. Separate figures showed
manufacturing growth in the Philadelphia region unexpectedly
eased in May to the slowest pace in seven months, a sign the  U.S.
economy  may get less of a boost from the industry that led it
out of its last recession.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index lost 2.2 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with gains of 6.8 percent by the S&P
500 and 1.5 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the
Asian benchmark are valued at 13.5 times estimated earnings on
average, compared with 13.6 times for the S&P 500 and 11.2 times
for the Stoxx 600.  Crude oil for June delivery tumbled 1.7 percent to $98.44 a
barrel in New York yesterday. The London Metal Exchange Index of
prices for six industrial metals including copper and aluminum
declined 1.7 percent yesterday.  The yen depreciated to 117.11 against the euro, compared
with 116.48 at the close of stock trading in  Tokyo  yesterday.
Against the dollar, Japan’s currency weakened to 81.83 from
81.68. A weaker yen boosts the value of overseas income at
Japanese companies when converted into their home currency.  To contact the reporters on this story:
